## Grants to Airlines ✈️ ️ 

According to the [Department of the Treasury](https://home.treasury.gov/policy-issues/coronavirus/assisting-american-industry/payroll-support-program-payments): 

> Funds received by [PSP] must exclusively be used for the continuation of payment of employee wages, salaries, and benefits. 

There were three separate PSP programs, with the government handing out payments over the course of year from 2020/20/04 - 2021/22/04 (not including a single payment for \$300,000 that was given in 2022 for some reason). According to the Treasury, "PSP1 provided assistance to over **600** companies, supporting *hundreds of thousands* of aviation jobs." As CEO of American Airlines Doug Parker stated in [December 2021](https://www.reuters.com/business/aerospace-defense/us-airlines-defend-54-billion-covid-19-government-lifeline-2021-12-15/), "It's not an exaggeration to say the program saved the airline industry." 

However, the extent to which the Payroll Support Program accomplished this remains debatable, including whether airlines were deserving of such generous funds in the first place. 

#### Quick Sidenotes 

While not all data was available in the previous section, it *is* for this section. Therefore, these are **conclusive** amounts.

As part of PSP, airlines had to pay back 26.2% of the total amount rewarded to them. These are considered loans, and are therefore not included in the data, but it should be noted that the total amount airlines received in sum is \$54 billion+. 

### Biggest Beneficiaries  

The treasury says they've assisted over 600 different airlines, but how were those funds distributed among them? 

```{r}
df %>%
  dplyr::filter(`Parent Sector` == "airlines") %>%
  dplyr::filter(`Grant Amount` > 100000000) %>%
  dplyr::group_by(`Parent Company`) %>%
  dplyr::summarise(Total = sum(`Grant Amount`),) %>%
  dplyr::arrange(Total) %>%
  e_chart(`Parent Company`) %>%
  e_bar(Total, bind = `Parent Company`) %>%
  e_flip_coords() %>%
  e_legend(show = FALSE) %>%
  e_title(
    "Four Airlines Received Nearly 80% of Total Awards",
    "COVID grant awards to airline industries (minimum $100 million)"
  ) %>%
  e_color("#0d5a74", background = "rgba(0, 0, 0, 0)") %>%
  e_tooltip(
    backgroundColor = "rgba(40, 40, 40, 0.75)",
    borderColor = "rgba(0, 0, 0, 0)",
    formatter = e_tooltip_item_formatter(style = "currency", currency = "USD"),
    textStyle = list(
      color = "#ffffff"
    )
  )
```

Nearly 79.5% of total funds went to just four companies; Southwest, United, Delta, and American airlines. Note that this amount includes a combined \$111 million in awards that was given to Wisconsin airlines, a company owned by United Airlines. 

ExpressJet, who received over \$100 million in awards, announced on [August 24th of 2022](https://www.flyingmag.com/expressjet-files-chapter-11-bankruptcy-furloughs-1300-pilots/) that they were filing for Chapter 11 Bankruptcy with intent to liquidate. 

### Billion Dollar Grants 

Despite comprising 17.2% of the \$244.6 billion in funds, only 786 individual grants have been handed out, or about 0.48% of the 163,592 that have been awarded in sum. 

Twelve awards have been for over \$1 billion - which also represents the 12 largest individual grants awarded across all companies. 

```{r}
df %>%
